* Definitions

We will use the following two-sided (bilateral) laplace transform notation:

$$ \BLTfull{F(x)} = \BLT{F(x)}(r) $$

And the following convolution for functions of a complex variable:

$$ \CVRfull{F}{G} = \CVR{F(r)}{G(r)} $$

Properties of these which will be used are:

\begin{align}
\CVR{\BLT{F}}{\BLT{G}} &= \BLT{FG} \\
\BLT{\deriv{x}^n F} &= r^n \BLT{F}
\end{align}

* Finding Fixed Points

The model:

\begin{align*}
\deriv{t}T &= -\beta TV \\
\deriv{t}E &= \beta TV - \frac{E}{\tauE} \\
\deriv{t}I &= \frac{E}{\tauE} - \frac{I}{\tauI} \\
\deriv{t}V &= pI - cV + D \deriv{x}^2 V + \nu \deriv{x} V \\
\end{align*}

To the moving frame $(x,t) \rightarrow (x^*,t^*)$:

\begin{align*}
\deriv{t^*}T^* &= -\beta T^*V^* + \alpha \deriv{x^*} T^* \\
\deriv{t^*}E^* &= \beta T^*V^* - \frac{E^*}{\tauE} + \alpha \deriv{x^*} E^* \\
\deriv{t^*}I^* &= \frac{E^*}{\tauE} - \frac{I^*}{\tauI} + \alpha \deriv{x^*} I^* \\
\deriv{t^*}V^* &= pI^* - cV^* + D \deriv{x^*}^2 V^* + (\nu+\alpha) \deriv{x^*}V^* \\
\end{align*}

Setting the time derivatives in the moving frame equal to zero yields
the conditions for a steady traveling wave solution, $A\zs(x)$

\begin{align*}
-\beta T\zs V\zs + \alpha \deriv{x^*} T\zs &= 0 \\
\beta T\zs V\zs - \frac{E\zs}{\tauE} + \alpha \deriv{x^*} E\zs &= 0 \\
\frac{E\zs}{\tauE} - \frac{I\zs}{\tauI} + \alpha \deriv{x^*} I\zs &= 0 \\
pI\zs - cV\zs + D \deriv{x^*}^2 V\zs + (\nu+\alpha) \deriv{x^*} V\zs &= 0 \\
\end{align*}

where we may now take the bilateral laplace transform over the real variable $x^*$, 
adopting the general notation $\BLT{F}=\scr{F}$:

\begin{align*}
-\beta \CVR{\scrzs{T}}{\scrzs{V}} + \alpha r\scrzs{T} &= 0 \\
\beta \CVR{\scrzs{T}}{\scrzs{V}} + (\alpha r - \frac{1}{\tauE})\scrzs{E} &= 0 \\
\frac{1}{\tauE}\scrzs{E} + (\alpha r - \frac{1}{\tauI})\scrzs{I} &= 0 \\
p\scrzs{I} + \left(Dr^2 + (\nu + \alpha)r - c\right)\scrzs{V} &= 0 \\
\end{align*}

Combining these four equations to find an expression for $\scrzs{V}$, we have:

$$ \scrzs{V} = -\frac{\alpha p}{\tauE}r\scrzs{T}
\left(\frac{1}{Dr^2 + (\nu + \alpha)r - c}\right)
\left(\frac{1}{\alpha r - \frac{1}{\tauI}}\right)
\left(\frac{1}{\alpha r - \frac{1}{\tauE}}\right) $$

Where again we may apply the fact $$ \beta\CVR{\scrzs{T}}{\scrzs{V}} = \alpha r\scrzs{T} $$ and so we have:

$$ r\scrzs{T} = -\frac{p\beta}{D\alpha^2\tauE} \CVR{\scrzs{T}} {\left[r\scrzs{T}
\left(\frac{1}{r^2 + \frac{\nu + \alpha}{D}r - \frac{c}{D}}\right)
\left(\frac{1}{r - \frac{1}{\alpha\tauI}}\right)
\left(\frac{1}{r - \frac{1}{\alpha\tauE}}\right)\right]}. $$

Now we recall our definition of the complex convolution and this becomes:

#+NAME: eqn:T
\begin{equation}
r\scrzs{T} = -\frac{p\beta}{D\alpha^2\tauE}
\frac{1}{2\pi i}\int_{-i\infty}^{i\infty} 
\frac{\xi\scrzs{T}(\xi)\scrzs{T}(r-\xi)}
{(\xi - r_1)(\xi - r_2)(\xi - r_3)(\xi - r_4)}d\xi
\end{equation}

where we have identified the four poles of the integrand:

$$ r_{1,2} = -\frac{\nu+\alpha}{2D} \mp \sqrt{\left(\frac{\nu+\alpha}{2D}\right)^2+\frac{c}{D}}, $$
$$ r_3 = \frac{1}{\alpha\tauE},$$   $$r_4 = \frac{1}{\alpha\tauI}. $$

Here we refer to the residue theorem, which tells us that any closed
counter-clockwise contour integral around $N$ poles of a meromorphic
function has the value

$$2\pi{}i\sum_{k=1}^N\res{a_k}.$$

Here, $\res{a_k}$ is the residue of the integrand at pole $a_k$, which can be
found via Cauchy's integral formula:

$$\frac{1}{2\pi{}i}\oint{}\frac{f(z)}{z-a}dz=f(a).$$

Looking at equation [[eqn:T]], the contour integral will contain the
vertical line $\operatorname{Re}(\xi)=0$, and may enclose just $r_1$,
since this is the only negative pole, or $r_2$, $r_3$, and $r_4$,
where the countour would be clockwise and thus the negative of the
counter-clockwise integral. Since we will be evaluating the numerator
of the integrand in eq. [[eqn:T]] at the value of each enclosed pole, we can
rule out one of the previously mentioned cases. If the only pole
enclosed is $r_1$, then, since $r_1$ is negative, the bilateral
laplace transform $\scrzs{T}$ evaluated at $\xi=r_1$ does not converge
under the assumption that

$$ \lim_{x\to\infty}T\zs(x) = T_1 > 0,$$

where $T_1$ is the maximum target cell density. Thus we are led to the
case that $r_2$, $r_3$, and $r_4$ are enclosed:

#+NAME: eqn:T2
\begin{equation}
r\scrzs{T}=\frac{p\beta}{D\alpha^2\tauE}\sum_{k=2,3,4}r_kR_k\scrzs{T}|_{r=r_k}\scrzs{T}(r-r_k)
\end{equation}

Where we have defined the constants $R_k$ for convenience:

$$ \frac{1}{R_k} = \prod_{n\neq k}(r_k-r_n)$$

And now we take the inverse of the bilateral laplace transform for
both sides of equation [[eqn:T2]], first observing the property:

$$ \BLT{F(x)}(r-a)=\BLT{e^{ax}F(x)}(r) $$

So we are left now with an expression for the derivative of $T\zs$:

\begin{align}
\deriv{x^*}{T\zs} &= \frac{p\beta}{D\alpha^2\tauE}T\zs\sum_{k=2,3,4}\scrzs{T}|_{r=r_k}r_kR_ke^{r_kx} \\
\ln{T\zs} &= \ln{T_1} + \frac{p\beta}{D\alpha^2\tauE}\sum_{k=2,3,4}\scrzs{T}|_{r=r_k}R_ke^{r_kx} \\
\end{align}

Where the general expression for a fixed wave solution of target cells
is written (with the Einstein summation convention)

\begin{equation}
T\zs = T_1e^{\frac{p\beta}{D\alpha^2\tauE}\scrzs{T}|_{r=r_k}R_ke^{r_kx}}
\end{equation}

or, equivalently:

\begin{equation}
T\zs = T_1\exp\left(\frac{p\beta}{D\alpha^2\tauE}\scrzs{T}|_{r=r_k}R_k\exp(r_kx)\right)
\end{equation}
